posts.cooked: Hi there! I'm just curious, did most teams create their own CAD elevator models or did they base their design on a WCP Product? Some elevators look complex to create, so I was wondering if you could share some good starting resources.

posts.name: Pizzatc
posts.cooked: We CADed our own based off some other teams' models.

posts.name: Isaac Proctor
posts.cooked: This year, we purchased a WCP 2-Stage GreyT Cascade Elevator. We obtained the CAD files online and incorporated them into our part libraries, adjusting various dimensions to fit our robotic requirements. To accommodate the design, we created additional components, including brackets, using a part library. Measurements were derived from our master blueprint and integrated seamlessly into our overall system. While the process was time-intensive, the results were satisfactory, and we avoided significant issues throughout the project.

posts.name: James Lyon
posts.cooked: Large configurable assemblies are generally beneficial, particularly for adding intricate details like elevators to CAD models. However, improper setup can result in complications due to misconfigured dependencies between component parts within the same studio. Additionally, Onshape exhibits a peculiar behavior where new assembly elements require manual configuration, often reverting to default settings if not addressed promptly. While this may occur in my situation, I remain open to the possibility of these assemblies being advantageous again, given their potential to streamline operations under suitable conditions.

posts.name: Nick Aarestad
posts.cooked: We designed our 2025 elevator using a combination of COTS parts and custom elements. Due to this, we incorporated both configurable and non-configurable parts for our 2025 robot. Some configurable components are available here [links removed]. While elevators can seem highly complex, approaching them methodically—by breaking them down into manageable parts—can simplify the process. We focused on reusable elements like the end/stop assembly, which, though not physically connected in our CAD, can remain constrained for consistency. This ensures uniformity across all elevator components, reducing potential rope-related issues. Elevator design often requires creativity and adaptability; by studying existing solutions, we can build upon proven designs while tailoring them to meet unique needs. Ultimately, sometimes stepping outside the box leads to innovative solutions.
